          From Wikipedia, the free encyclopedia                            Jump to:     navigation,      search            Giorgos Pavlidis   Γιώργος Παυλίδης         Regional Governor of Eastern Macedonia and Thrace    Incumbent    Assumed office 1 September 2014   Preceded by Aris Giannakidis   Prefect of Xanthi   In office 1 January 1999 – 31 December 2010   Personal details   Born 1956 (1956)   Political party Nea Dimokratia   Alma mater Democritus University of Thrace   Profession Lawyer   Giorgos Pavlidis (Greek: Γιώργος Παυλίδης; born 1956) is a Greek politician of Nea Dimokratia. The long-standing Prefect of Xanthi was narrowly defeated in the 2010 local election, but was elected Governor of the region of Eastern Macedonia and Thrace in the subsequent 2014 election. Biography[edit] Born 1956, Giorgos Pavlidis studied at Democritus University of Thrace graduating in law. Following his studies, he practised as a criminal defense lawyer and later contended for the rights of syndicalists, workers and farmers.[1] He was for the first time elected a member of the prefectural council of Xanthi in 1985, served in the local government since 1998. Running on a platform named "Renaissance" (Αναγέννηση) and supported by Nea Dimokratia, he was elected Prefect of Xanthi in the 1998 prefectural election, to be reelected in 2002 and 2006.[1] In 2004 Pavlidis initiated the Cross-border cooperation network of neighboring Greek, Bulgarian and Turkish prefectures, based in Orestiada.[1] Nominated by the Union of Prefectural Administrations of Greece, Pavlidis has been the head of the Greek delegation to the Congress of the Council of Europe from 2007 until 2012, where he affiliates with the European People's Party group.[2] When in 2010 Greek prefectures were set to be abolished as part of the Kallikratis reform, he contended the 2010 regional election but was narrowly defeated by the prefect of Rodopi, Aris Giannakidis. In the subsequent 2014 regional election, he however clearly defeated the incumbent Giannakidis with 56.34% in the second round.[3] References[edit]   ^ a b c Βιογραφικό [Βιογραφικό] (in Greek). Giorgos Pavlidis. Retrieved 10 April 2015.  ^ "National delegation: Greece". Congress of the Council of Europe. Archived from the original on 14 February 2009.  ^ "Local elections: Dourou wins Attica, Kaminis reelected in Athens". To Vima. 26 May 2014. Retrieved 10 April 2015.    External links[edit]  Official website (Greek)          v t e   Regional governors of Greece          Rena Dourou (Attica) Kostas Bakoyannis (Central Greece) Apostolos Tzitzikostas (Central Macedonia) Stavros Arnaoutakis (Crete) Giorgos Pavlidis (Eastern Macedonia and Thrace) Alexandros Kachrimanis (el) (Epirus) Theodoros Galiatsatos (Ionian Islands) Christiana Kalogirou (North Aegean) Petros Tatoulis (Peloponnese) Georgios Chatzimarkos (South Aegean) Konstantinos Agorastos (el) (Thessaly) Apostolos Katsifaras (Western Greece) Theodoros Karypidis (Western Macedonia)                            Retrieved from "https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Giorgos_Pavlidis&oldid=725453429"          Categories: 1956 birthsLiving peopleGreek lawyersDemocritus University of Thrace alumniPrefects of XanthiRegional governors of GreeceHidden categories: CS1 uses Greek-language script (el)CS1 Greek-language sources (el)Use dmy dates from April 2015Articles containing Greek-language textArticles with Greek-language external linksInterlanguage link template link number            
